  <h2>Augusta: Historic Small Town with Character</h2>
  <p>Augusta is Butler County, 20 miles east of Wichita, about 9,500 people. Small town with real character and history — oil heritage, close-knit community, El Dorado Lake nearby for recreation. The housing stock is mostly older, 1900s-1950s construction, solid brick and wood, good bones but aging. Price range is $90k-$180k. It's a real small town where families have roots, not a bedroom suburb.</p>
  <p>Augusta sellers are often longtime residents, estate sales from original town families, heirs inheriting property, or people relocating to Wichita for work who need fast exits.</p>

  <h2>Augusta Housing Market: Historic Homes and Small-Town Character</h2>
  <p>Augusta's dominated by older construction — 1900s-1950s brick homes with character, solid foundations, original details. Small-town feel, tight-knit community, lower price points. $90k-$180k typically. Homes are well-maintained by longtime residents but aging. Original electrical, plumbing, heating systems. Some historic value, but also deferred maintenance on older properties.</p>
  <p>The market's quieter than suburbs closer to Wichita. Properties sit longer on traditional listings. But when the right buyer and seller connect, it moves. I understand Augusta's market and these homes specifically.</p>

  <h2>Who I Buy From in Augusta</h2>
  <p>Longtime Augusta residents ready to downsize or retire out of Kansas. Estate sales from families who've owned the same Augusta house for 40-50 years. Heirs inheriting downtown properties from parents. People relocating to Wichita for work who need to sell Augusta property fast. Small-town folks facing financial pressure or life changes. Historic home owners dealing with maintenance costs and system failures.</p>

